<DOC><DOCNO> AP891006-0077 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-10-06-89 1056EDT</FILEID><FIRST>u i BC-EastGermany-Chronology 1stLd-Writethru a0551 10-06 0516</FIRST><SECOND>BC-East Germany-Chronology, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0551,0529</SECOND><HEAD>Major Events in East German History</HEAD><HEAD>Eds: Subs 12th graf, `September 1972...,' with 1 graf to CORRECTyear U.S. and East Germany established ties. Pickup 13th pvs, `Sept. 7...'</HEAD><DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The following is a chronology of the major eventsleading up to and following the founding of the East German state40 years ago:   May 1945: Nazi Germany surrenders unconditionally to Alliedforces. Germany is divided into zones occupied by the victoriousallied powers. The region that is now East Germany comes under thejurisdiction of the Soviet Union.   April 1946: The East German Communist Party becomes thegoverning political force in the country. Its leaders come from theanti-Hitler communist resistance members who were imprisoned orexiled.   May 1949: The Allied powers form a new German state, the FederalRepublic of Germany, or West Germany.   Oct. 7, 1949: The German Democratic Republic, or East Germany,is officially founded as an independent state in the Soviet zone ofoccupation.   Oct. 10, 1949: The Soviet military administration transfers alladministrative powers to the new communist government.   June 17, 1953: East German workers unhappy with poor pay,increased working hours and government oppression stage revolts inseveral East German cities. The uprising is put down with the helpof Soviet tanks, and now described in official East Germanhistories as an ``attempted counterrevolutionary coup.''   Aug. 13, 1961: Faced with a record exodus of highly skilled EastGerman workers, the government begins erecting the Berlin Wall andseals the border with West Germany. The government justifies theaction by saying hostile capitalist forces were attempting toplunder East Germany and that espionage and terrorist organizationswere operating out of West Berlin.   May 1971: Erich Honecker becomes first secretary of theCommunist Party.   Dec. 21, 1972: East Germany and West Germany sign a treaty toimprove inter-German relations and to ease travel between the twocountries.   Sept. 18, 1973: East Germany becomes a member of the UnitedNations.   September 1974: The United States and East Germany establishdiplomatic relations, bringing to 100 the number of countries withwhich East Germany has official relations.   Sept. 7, 1987: Honecker becomes the first East German leader topay an official visit to West Germany.   August and September 1989: Tens of thousands of East Germansseeking passage to West Germany begin pouring into West Germanembassies in Hungary, Czechoslovakia and Poland.   Sept. 10, 1989: The exodus begins as Hungary agrees to open itsborders to East German citizens.   Sept. 30, 1989: East and West Germany agree that refugees holedup at the West German embassies in Prague and Warsaw will beallowed to leave for the West, following thousands who left whenHungary opened its border. More than 45,000 East Germans arrive inWest Germany by early October.   Oct. 4, 1989: About 10,000 would-be emigrants clash with riotpolice in Dresden, followed by another demonstration one day later.   Oct. 6-7, 1989: East Germany holds celebrations marking its 40thanniversary in ceremonies overshadowed by the refugee exodus. Thehard-line government rejects the need for democratic reforms.</TEXT></DOC>